<h2>The 10 Most Important Schema Types</h2>
<p>Not all schema types carry equal weight. Focus on the ones that trigger rich results and match your content.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Essential schema markup types for SEO with priority levels" src="/images/blog/schema-types-table.webp" /></p>
<h3>Organization Schema</h3>
<p>Every website needs Organization schema. It defines your business name, logo, website URL, social media profiles, and contact information. Google uses this data for Knowledge Panels.</p>
<p><strong>Properties to include:</strong> name, url, logo, sameAs (social profiles), contactPoint, address, description.</p>
<h3>LocalBusiness Schema</h3>
<p>For any business with a physical location, LocalBusiness schema is essential. It feeds Google your address, phone number, hours, price range, and service area. This data powers map pack listings and local search results.</p>
<p>For a full guide on local SEO optimization, read our <a href="/blog/optimize-google-business-profile/">Google Business Profile guide</a>.</p>
<h3>Article and BlogPosting Schema</h3>
<p>Every blog post and article should include Article or BlogPosting schema. It tells Google the headline, author, publication date, modified date, and featured image. This data enables article-style rich results with dates and author information.</p>
<p>For blog-specific schema implementation, read our <a href="/blog/schema-markup-for-blog-posts/">schema markup for blog posts guide</a>.</p>
<h3>Product Schema</h3>
<p>E-commerce pages need Product schema with price, availability, currency, brand, and review data. Product rich results show pricing and stock status directly in search. These are among the highest-converting rich results.</p>
<h3>FAQPage Schema</h3>
<p>FAQPage schema marks up question-and-answer pairs. Google can display expandable FAQ sections directly in search results. Note: since 2024, Google restricts FAQ rich results to authoritative government and health websites for most queries. But the schema still helps AI systems understand your FAQ content.</p>
<h3>HowTo Schema</h3>
<p>HowTo schema marks up step-by-step instructions. Google can display numbered steps, time estimates, and required tools in search results. This works well for tutorial and guide content.</p>
<h3>BreadcrumbList Schema</h3>
<p>BreadcrumbList schema displays your site's navigation hierarchy in search results. Instead of showing a plain URL like <code>example.com/blog/schema-markup-seo-guide</code>, Google shows a clickable trail: Home &gt; Blog &gt; SEO Tips &gt; Schema Markup Guide.</p>
<p>BreadcrumbList is one of the easiest schema types to implement site-wide. Add it to your page template once and it applies to every page automatically. The SEO benefit is universal across all content types.</p>
<p>For proper site architecture and <a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">internal linking</a>, breadcrumbs reinforce the hierarchical structure that Google uses to understand your content organization.</p>
<h3>Review and AggregateRating Schema</h3>
<p>Review schema displays star ratings in search results. AggregateRating shows the average score and total review count. Star ratings in search results are among the most powerful CTR boosters. Follow our <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">guide to getting more Google reviews</a> to build the review volume that makes this schema valuable.</p>
<h3>Event Schema</h3>
<p>Event schema marks up events with dates, locations, ticket prices, and performers. Google displays event cards with dates and venues directly in search results. Essential for businesses that host events, workshops, webinars, or conferences.</p>
<p>Include the event name, start date, end date, location (with address), ticket URL, and price range. Google uses this data to display your events in dedicated event search results and Google Maps event listings.</p>
<h3>VideoObject Schema</h3>
<p>VideoObject schema marks up video content with title, description, thumbnail, duration, and upload date. Google can display video thumbnails in search results. Video-rich results stand out visually and earn significantly higher click-through rates than text-only listings.</p>
<p>Include the video name, description, thumbnail URL, upload date, duration, and content URL. If your content includes embedded YouTube or Vimeo videos, VideoObject schema helps Google surface them in video search results.</p>
<h2>How to Add Schema Markup to Your Website</h2>
<p>Adding schema markup is simpler than most people think. JSON-LD is the recommended format. It goes in your HTML <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> section without changing any visible content.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="5 steps to implement schema markup on your website" src="/images/blog/schema-implementation-steps.webp" /></p>
<h3>Step 1: Choose Your Schema Type</h3>
<p>Start with the types most relevant to your business:</p>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Business Type</th>
<th>Start With These Schema Types</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Local business</td>
<td>Organization + LocalBusiness + BreadcrumbList</td>
</tr>
