<h3>Step 2: Generate the JSON-LD Code</h3>
<p>Use a schema generator tool to create the code. Several free options exist:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.google.com/webmasters/markup-helper/">Google Structured Data Markup Helper</a></li>
<li><a href="https://technicalseo.com/tools/schema-markup-generator/">TechnicalSEO.com Schema Generator</a></li>
<li><a href="https://schemantra.com/">Schemantra JSON-LD Generator</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Enter your business information. The tool generates the JSON-LD code block.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="JSON-LD schema markup code example for a local business" src="/images/blog/schema-json-ld-example.webp" /></p>
<h3>Step 3: Add the Code to Your Website</h3>
<p>Paste the JSON-LD code block into your page's HTML <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> section inside a <code>&lt;script type="application/ld+json"&gt;</code> tag.</p>
<p><strong>For WordPress:</strong> Use a plugin like Rank Math, Yoast SEO, or Schema Pro. These add schema automatically without editing code. Rank Math handles most schema types out of the box and auto-generates Article schema for every post.</p>
<p><strong>For Astro, Next.js, or static sites:</strong> Add the JSON-LD script directly to your page template or head component. Create a reusable schema component that accepts props for the specific data. This keeps your schema consistent and easy to update across hundreds of pages.</p>
<p><strong>For Shopify:</strong> Use the built-in structured data or a schema app from the Shopify App Store. Most Shopify themes include basic Product schema. Apps like JSON-LD for SEO add Organization, BreadcrumbList, and FAQPage schema automatically.</p>
<p><strong>For Webflow:</strong> Add custom code in the page settings head section. Webflow does not have native schema support, so you need to add JSON-LD manually or use a third-party integration.</p>
<h3>Step 4: Validate Your Markup</h3>
<p>After adding schema, validate it using 2 tools:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong><a href="https://search.google.com/test/rich-results">Google Rich Results Test</a>:</strong> Checks if your schema qualifies for rich results</li>
<li><strong><a href="https://validator.schema.org/">Schema.org Validator</a>:</strong> Validates the technical correctness of your markup</li>
</ul>
<p>Fix any errors or warnings before moving on. Common issues include missing required properties, incorrect data types, and mismatched values.</p>
<h3>Step 5: Monitor in Google Search Console</h3>
<p>Google Search Console reports schema errors and rich result performance. Check the "Enhancements" section for issues. Monitor which pages earn rich results and which have errors.</p>
<p>For a full Search Console setup and monitoring guide, read our <a href="/blog/google-search-console-guide/">Google Search Console guide</a>.</p>
