<h2>Schema Markup and AI Search</h2>
<p>In 2026, schema markup does more than earn rich results in Google. It makes your content readable to AI systems that power the next generation of search.</p>
<p>Google AI Overviews, ChatGPT web search, Perplexity, and Gemini all pull structured data from websites. When your page has clear schema markup, AI models can extract facts with confidence instead of interpreting unstructured text.</p>
<h3>How Schema Helps AI Cite Your Content</h3>
<p>AI systems prefer sources with clear, machine-readable data. Schema markup provides:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Entity clarity.</strong> AI knows your business name, type, location, and offerings without guessing.</li>
<li><strong>Fact extraction.</strong> Prices, ratings, hours, and specifications are structured as data, not buried in paragraphs.</li>
<li><strong>Source attribution.</strong> When AI cites a specific claim, structured data makes your page the obvious source.</li>
</ul>
<p>Sites with proper schema get cited in AI-generated answers 67% more often according to recent research. For more on AI search optimization, read our <a href="/blog/get-cited-ai-search/">guide to getting cited in AI search</a>.</p>
<h3>Schema Types That Matter Most for AI</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Organization</strong> and <strong>Person</strong> schema help AI identify who you are</li>
<li><strong>Article</strong> schema helps AI understand publication context and authorship</li>
<li><strong>FAQPage</strong> schema provides pre-structured Q&amp;A pairs AI models can directly use</li>
<li><strong>HowTo</strong> schema gives AI structured step-by-step instructions to reference</li>
</ul>
<p>Read our <a href="/blog/optimize-google-ai-overviews/">guide to optimizing for AI Overviews</a> for the complete AI search playbook.</p>
<h2>Common Schema Markup Mistakes</h2>
<p>Most schema implementations have errors that prevent rich results from appearing. Avoid these.</p>
<p><strong>Missing required properties.</strong> Every schema type has required and recommended properties. Leaving out required ones causes validation failures. Always check <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/structured-data/intro-structured-data">Google's structured data documentation</a> for requirements.</p>
<p><strong>Marking up hidden content.</strong> Schema should describe content visible on the page. Do not add schema for content in hidden divs, popups, or elements users cannot see. Google flags this as deceptive.</p>
<p><strong>Self-serving review markup.</strong> You cannot add Review schema to your own product on your own website based on your own assessment. Reviews must come from third parties. Google penalizes self-referential review markup.</p>
<p><strong>Incorrect data types.</strong> A price must be a number, not text like "Contact us for pricing." A date must follow ISO 8601 format (YYYY-MM-DD). Incorrect types cause silent failures.</p>
<p><strong>Duplicate or conflicting schema.</strong> Multiple schema blocks with conflicting information confuse Google. Your Organization schema and LocalBusiness schema should not show different addresses or phone numbers.</p>
<p><strong>Not updating schema when content changes.</strong> If your hours, pricing, or services change, update your schema to match. Outdated schema misleads users and Google. Run regular <a href="/blog/how-to-do-seo-audit/">SEO audits</a> that include schema validation.</p>
